Credit cards aren’t bad. 
They are simply a tool that we can use with our money.

But what are you do if you have credit card debt and you want to pay it off? 

The best thing you can do is to actually STOP using your credit card for a period of time.

Yes, this means you might have to take the time to switch all your bills over to your debit card if they are currently on your credit card. 

➡️ But here’s the deal:

Money isn’t just about math. Money is about emotions as well. 

When you’re working to pay off credit card debt, it can be frustrating to see your balance either stay the same or not go down as quickly as you possibly can. 

That’s why it helps to stop using your credit card and focus solely on paying your balance off. 

What are your thoughts? Do you agree?

Stay tuned for Part 2 on how to tackle impulse spending!

Do you feel GUILT when you spend money? 

This feeling is especially around the holidays. 

Let’s talk about WHY.

Feeling guilty when you spend money comes from unintentional, unplanned spending. It also comes from not having clear goals and a clear reason for wanting to reach those goals. 

Here are 3 things you can start focusing on to help your future self combat guilt: 

1️⃣ Start building up your savings accounts: Emergency Fund AND Sinking Funds for things like Christmas, birthdays, and vacations.

2️⃣ Make sure you’re creating a budget for EVERY paycheck and giving every dollar you own a job

3️⃣ Give yourself a specific line item in your budget for a BUFFER and for personal spending

Which of these will you try?

Knowledge kills Fear. 

What are you afraid of when it comes to your finances? 

Instead of running from these things or shrinking back in shame and avoidance, I want you to ask yourself:

“How can I learn more about this?” 

Once you learn and obtain the knowledge, then there’s NO room for fear because you have the upper hand, you have a plan, and you know what to do. And that’s when you become unstoppable! 

What are you afraid of when it comes to your money? 
Let me know in the comments below ⤵️

Your bank accounts should be organized based on your unique needs and financial goals!

If you struggle with overspending, then I want you to try this method!

Make account 1️⃣ your income account. All your paychecks go here.

Make Account 2️⃣ your bills account. All your fixed expenses are paid from this account. 

After totaling up all your fixed expenses, set up an automatic transfer from account 1️⃣ to account 2️⃣. 

That way, you’re not tempted to overspend money that should actually be going to bills!

Let’s talk about this budget!
This woman wrote to me and said “we live paycheck to paycheck and can’t get out of this rut. We should have tons of money leftover every month but we waste it on who knows what.”

This is SO COMMON. People feel like they make good money but have nothing to show for it. Have you ever felt this way?

Here are my budget suggestions:
1️⃣ There’s definitely room for you to cut some of your spending such as YouTube TV, internet (maybe there’s a cheaper option out there), and search for cheaper cell phone options.
2️⃣ Depending on how many kids are adults, you could consider charging them rent to help cover utilities. Even just $200 a month is manageable for a working adult and could cover some of the bills.
3️⃣ I’m not sure how old this couple is, but it’s time to start beefing up their retirement. By cutting costs and extra “rent” from their adult children, they can send a good amount to a 401K or Roth IRA.
4️⃣ Start tracking your spending ASAP. You’re right…you should have more money left over at the end of the month. We need to find out where that money is going!

THINGS TO NOTE (a few details she gave me):
✨ The car will be paid off in a year. YAY!
✨ Their credit card doesn’t carry much of a balance. They use it to help boost their credit score. (Be sure to pay it off in full each month!)
✨ They have $60K left on student loans. If any of them are PRIVATE student loans, consider refinancing to a lower interest rate!

I truly believe that if this couple doubles down on their money habits, spending, and saving that they will be in a completely different position in just one year!!!

You can’t do it all! 

Or at least, very few people can. 

That’s why prioritizing is KEY when it comes to managing your money. Because not everything you want or need is of equal importance. 

If you’re struggling to decide how to prioritize your spending, then I want to encourage you to:

1. Make sure your emergency fund is in place (3 months of your bare bones budget is a good rule of thumb!)
2. Start layering in your other goals like sending extra money to debt, sinking funds, and investing. 

Don’t let all the options paralyze you from taking action. Start with one small goal, then once you accomplish that, celebrate and move on to the next one!

Let’s be honest here, your credit score matters. Here’s why:

Your credit score helps lenders know whether or not you’re going to be a good candidate for a loan. So whether you’re applying for credit cards, a house loan, a personal loan, or looking to purchase a car or refinance, your credit score is going to impact the interest rates that you get on these loans. My husband I refinanced our home last year and our credit scores played a huge factor in us being able to refinance from a 30 year mortgage to a 15 year mortgage while getting a low interest rate.

And if you’re a renter, your landlord might even look at your credit score to determine whether or not they want you as a renter.

Ultimately, your credit score is a three digit number that communicates a person’s credit worthiness. The higher your credit score, the better you appear to a lender, landlord or a credit card company. The lower your score, the riskier you appear.

Are you new to the world of investing? 
Don’t worry, we’ve got you covered! 

Here are four essential things you need to keep in mind before you dive in.

1️⃣ First, let’s get one thing straight: investing is NOT a get-rich-quick scheme. You might hear people talking about overnight fortunes, but the truth is, investing is a marathon, not a sprint. It takes time and patience to see your investments grow and pay off in the long run. So, be cautious of anyone who promises you quick returns - they’re probably not someone you want to trust with your hard-earned money.

2️⃣ Diversification is key! One way to do this is by investing in Index Funds, which allow you to spread your investments and minimize the risk of losing money.

3️⃣ Fees matter more than you think. High fees can eat into your returns, so it’s important to keep an eye on them. Typically, anything over 1% is considered high, so be sure to choose investments with lower fees where possible.

4️⃣ Finally, don’t try to time the market. It’s tempting to try and predict when stocks will rise or fall, but in reality, no one can predict the future. Instead, focus on investing for the long term and stick to your investment plan. Remember, time in the market beats timing the market.

Let's talk about IRAs and Roth IRAs and clear up the confusion, no fancy jargon involved! 

💰First up, we have the traditional IRA. 

It's like a time-traveling savings account. You contribute with money before paying taxes on it. So, you get a tax deduction in the year you make the contributions. 

But here's the catch: when you retire and withdraw the money, you'll have to pay taxes on the whole shebang, including any growth. 💸

💰Now, let's talk Roth IRA. 

It's the modern-day superstar of retirement accounts. With a Roth IRA, you contribute with money you've already paid taxes on. So, no tax deductions upfront. 

But guess what? When you retire and start taking out the money, it's tax-free! Yes, you heard it right—no taxes on your withdrawals, including any investment earnings. 🙌

In 2023 you can contribute up to $6,500 per year. But if you're 50 or older, you get a little extra boost! You can contribute up to $7,500 per year. 💪📆

So, whether you go the traditional IRA route or choose the Roth IRA path, it's all about finding the right fit for your financial journey.

In Part 1, we introduced you to a single woman from Jersey City with a take-home pay of $4,198 and $36,000 in credit card debt. Let’s tackle those credit cards. 💳

Her Bank of America card is maxed out with a balance of $28,500 at a 23.24% interest rate. Her Capital One card is slightly “better,” carrying a $7,500 balance at a 20.74% interest rate.

These debts won’t just vanish - they need a strategy. 

Here are three options:

1️⃣ Debt Avalanche Method: Tackle the debt with the highest interest first—in this case, the Bank of America card. 

2️⃣ Balance Transfer Credit Card: Move her debts to a card with a low or zero introductory rate, and aggressively pay it off in that period. Caution: This requires self-discipline—pause using your cards if you’re in debt.

3️⃣ Debt Consolidation Loan: Combine all credit card debts into one loan with a single monthly payment, usually at a lower interest rate.

The common denominator in all these methods? 

✨Commitment and consistency.✨ 

The journey out of debt might look like a marathon, but every step counts.
